<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900814-0096</DOCNO><DOCID>900814-0096.</DOCID><HL>   Mobil Will Buy   Australian Assets   From Exxon Corp.   ----   By Allanna Sullivan   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/14/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   MOB XON</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)PETROLEUM (PET)OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Mobil Corp. said it agreed to purchase thestake it doesn't already own in two refineries and a networkof gasoline stations in Australia from Exxon Corp.   Neither Exxon nor Mobil would disclose the transaction'svalue, but industry officials put it at about $400 million.</LP><TEXT>   The purchase includes about 300 gasoline stations and 90fuel truck depots. Mobil already owns 700 gasoline stationsthere.   In addition, the acquisition includes Exxon's 35% share ofa joint-venture company currently operated by both companies.The company, Petroleum Refineries Proprietary Ltd., runs tworefineries. One, located in Altona, processes 120,000 barrelsa day of crude oil. The other refinery, in Adelaide, handles65,000 barrels of oil daily.   Mobil has been attempting to increase its presence inAustralia and Asia, where the use of oil has increasedsharply in recent years. &quot;The acquisition of these assetswill advance our strategy of increasing strength in theworld's fastest-growing market for petroleum products,&quot; saidAllen Murray, Mobil chairman.   The acquisition, expected to be completed by year end,will boost Mobil to a tie with British Petroleum Co. as thesecond-largest marketer of gasoline in Australia. It will beproviding service to 20% of Australia's motorists. Mobil iscurrently ranked fourth, serving 14% of the populace.</TEXT></DOC>